'''''Morchella anatolica''''' is a species of [[ascomycete]] fungus in the family [[Morchellaceae]] that was described as new to science in 2010. It is found in Southwest [[Anatolia]], Turkey, where it grows on moss-covered stream beds in [[pine]] forests. The [[ascocarp|fruit bodies]] grow to {{convert|30|–|35|mm|in|abbr=on}} tall and {{convert|8|–|10|mm|in|abbr=on}} wide. They are roughly conical, with fleshy longitudinal ribs that lack the cross-ribs characteristic of most other ''[[Morchella]]'' species. Young specimens have a light [[lilac (color)|lilac]] tint that darkens or turns grayish in maturity.<ref name="Işıloğlu 2020"/>

The [[ascospore]]s of this fungus are [[ellipsoid]] to broadly ellipsoid, [[hyaline]] (translucent), and measure 24–30 by 18–18&nbsp;[[micrometre|µm]]; these dimensions are relatively large for the genus ''Morchella''. Fine longitudinal grooves are present on the surface of mature spores. The spores are produced in groups of eight in cylindrical to club-shaped [[ascus|asci]] measuring 290–310 by 18–26&nbsp;µm.<ref name="Işıloğlu 2020"/>

''M. anatolica'' has also been found in [[Spain]], and is closely related to ''[[Morchella rufobrunnea|M. rufobrunnea]]''.<ref name=Richard2014/>

